{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"31bf038a-9b63-4df2-8c7b-5d4cad1ab0b1","content":"In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the `Window` object:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Created\");\n    window.Activated += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Activated\");\n    window.Deactivated += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Deactivated\");\n    window.Stopped += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Stopped\");\n    window.Resumed += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Resumed\");\n    window.Destroying += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Destroying\");\n    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Backgrounding\");\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Typical transition order:**\n\n| Scenario | Events |\n|----------|--------|\n| App launch | Created → Activated |\n| Switch away | Deactivated → Stopped |\n| Return to app | Resumed → Activated |\n| Close app | Stopped → Destroying |\n\n> `Backgrounding` fires only on iOS/Mac Catalyst (use it to save state via `BackgroundingEventArgs.State`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"92c67567-8c50-4530-bb33-ef5fd831a0f6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about subscribing to Window lifecycle events in a .NET MAUI app for debugging/logging purposes. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI that I can answer directly without needing to search the codebase.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the `Window` class exposes several lifecycle events that correspond to the app's window state transitions. Let me provide a concise, helpful answer.\n\nThe key Window lifecycle events in .NET MAUI are:\n- `Created` - window is created\n- `Activated` - window gains focus\n- `Deactivated` - window loses focus\n- `Stopped` - window is no longer visible\n\n\n- `Resumed` - window resumes from stopped state\n- `Destroying` - window is being destroyed\n- `Backgrounding` (iOS/Mac Catalyst only) - window moves to background\n\nNow I'll show how to subscribe to these events with a practical example.","outputTokens":547,"requestId":"A859:1BCBFD:66139B:7614BF:69FBE2B2"},"id":"74717e33-9873-4e06-a041-acd720bc33a8","timestamp":"2026-05-07T00:54:20.780Z","parentId":"47614d66-d0e1-4bc0-b562-500a2826139b"}
